<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1783,1952]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1855,1880]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus name (feminine) is derived from the valiant and proud North American native people known as the Cherokee (possibly from the 
<emphasis box="[636,867,1892,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Choctaw Cha-la-kee</emphasis>
meaning “people of the mountains” or 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Chi-luk-ikbi</emphasis>
meaning “people of the cave country”).
</paragraph>
